article.headline: BYU 88, New Mexico 71
article.story: PROVO, Utah (AP) -- Rafael Araujo scored 18 points and grabbed 8 rebounds to lead BYU to an 88-71 victory over New Mexico Saturday -- the Cougars' fifth win in a row. It was the 24th straight road loss for New Mexico dating back to the 2001-02 season. New Mexico coach Ritchie McKay met with his team for a long time after the loss and then expressed his displeasure with the Lobos' play. "We stunk in the second half, we stunk in the first half," said the second-year head coach in a post-game interview. "We didn't bring the effort." New Mexico moves on to play Utah on Monday and McKay promised some of the problems the Lobos encountered against BYU will be corrected. "I was very disappointed by our effort and we've mentioned it already," he said. "We'll have it changed by Monday night." The Lobos' defense, as it has most of the season on the road, had plenty of holes. BYU shot 60 percent for the game and the Cougars hit 15 of 22 shots in the second half. The Cougars also hit 9 of 17 3-pointers. McKay also brushed aside a suggestion by New Mexico play-by-play announcer Mike Roberts that the 6-foot-11, 280-pound Araujo had free reign inside. "The referees didn't have a hand in this," McKay said. Instead, McKay said the Lobos didn't play as a team. "For the first time, we went different ways," he said. BYU led 41-36 at the half, shooting 53.6 percent from the field while holding the Lobos to 40.7 percent shooting. But the Cougars (17-7, 7-4 Mountain West) stepped it up in the second half -- rattling in 68.2 percent of their shots, including 4 of 7 from 3-point range. BYU finished with 32 points in the paint, compared with 17 for the Lobos (13-10, 4-6). Troy DeVries scored 16 points for New Mexico, while Javin Tindall added 12 points and four assists. Mark Bigelow had 16 points, four assists and six rebounds for BYU, while Mike Hall chipped in 16 points and five boards. New Mexico junior center Danny Granger, the leading scorer in Mountain West Conference games, finished with 9 points and just 3 rebounds. Those numbers were well below his average of 20.8 points and 9 rebounds. "He let some of the adversity get in his head," McKay said. "He missed some shots and got frustrated. I've never seen Danny Granger get three rebounds."
